  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Facilitate information sharing and evidence collection\n- Enable extradition of suspects\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Encourage consistent legal frameworks\n- Develop common definitions of money laundering\n- Establish similar reporting and compliance requirements\n\n4. Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- National agencies that collect and analyze suspicious financial transactions\n- Exchange information internationally\n- Coordinate investigations across jurisdictions\n\n5. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Banks and financial institutions required to implement AML protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- International oversight and evaluation\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International economic sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Coordinated efforts to restrict financial activities of criminal networks\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating money laundering globally.",
